      <div xml:id="NA367-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaivu malintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how marriage is urged for.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA367">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            koṭuṅkaṭ kākkaik kūrvāyp pēṭai</l>
<l>            naṭuṅkuciṟaip piḷḷai taḻīik kiḷaipayirntu</l>
<l>            karuṅkaṭ karuṉaic cennel veṇcōṟu</l>
<l>            cūruṭaip paliyoṭu kavariya kuṟuṅkāṟ</l>
<l>            kūḻuṭai naṉmaṉaik kuḻuviṉa virukku</l>
<l>            mūti larumaṉ pēricaic ciṟukuṭi</l>
<l rend="indent4">            yaṉṉa naṉṉuta lāykō lavirtoṭi</l>
<l>            melliya larivainiṉ palliruṅ katuppiṟ</l>
<l>            kuvaḷaiyoṭu toṭutta naṟuvī mullait</l>
<l>            taḷaiyavi ḻalarit taṇṇaṟuṅ kōtai</l>
<l>            yiḷaiyaruñ cūṭi vantaṉar namarum</l>
<l>            viriyuḷai naṉmā kaṭaiip</l>
<l>            pariyātu varuvarip paṉipaṭu nāḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O young woman of soft nature,</l>
<l>{with shining bracelets in a choice row [and] with a forehead</l>
<l rend="indent">	as good as} Arumaṉ’s famous Ciṟukuṭi with old houses,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	where the sharp-beaked female of the cruel-eyed crow resides,</l>
<l rend="indent2">	embracing [its] young ones with shivering wings, calling [its] relatives,</l>
<l rend="indent3">	[all of them]<note place="foot">The plural <term xml:lang="ta">kuḻuviṉa</term> marks the fact that the rest of the clause refers to all the crows, not just the <term xml:lang="ta">pēṭai</term>.</note> crowding the good house on short stilts rich in food,</l>
<l rend="indent4">	in order to seize, along with the offering to the fearful deity(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cūr-uṭai</term>: here again we have to take -<term xml:lang="ta">uṭai</term> as a real genitive suffix, unless we want the <term xml:lang="ta">pali</term> to be called "fearful".</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">	white rice cooked from red paddy with blacke-eyed Karuṉai roots,</l>
<l>– [his] young [attendants] have come, wearing</l>
<l rend="indent">	cool fragrant garlands of unfolding blossoms</l>
<l rend="indent">	of the jasmine with fragrant blossoms, linked with blue waterlilies,</l>
<l rend="indent4">	[just] like [those] in your rich dark hair,</l>
<l>and our man too will come, speedily<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pariyātu</term> could either be analysed as an adverbial positive negative absolutive of <term xml:lang="ta">pari</term> "to run", or as a neg. absolutive of <term xml:lang="ta">pari</term> "to be distressed" (i.e. "without distress").</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">	impelling [his] broad-maned good horses,</l>
<l rend="indent4">	on this day of falling dews.</l>
      </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
